[The initial posting suggested the total number of those affected was higher (about 6000) with 9 deaths. As noted in the past, a hallmark of epidemic hepatitis E is a high case fatality rate in pregnant women (especially in the last trimester). Fulminant hepatic failure occurs in this cohort and may be caused by immunological and endocrinological changes occurring in pregnancy. In maternal survivors, infection of the baby occurs often. Deaths can also occur in those with preexisting liver disease of any type.

Treatment of some cases of hepatitis E virus (HEV) infection, acute or chronic, has been effective using ribivirin monotherapy (1). Additionally, a recombinant vaccine is being studied and appears to be safe and effective (2).

References:
1. Gerolani R, Borentain P, Raissouni F, et al: Treatment of severa acute hepatitis E with ribavirin. J Clin Micribiol 2011;52;60-62.
2. Zhu FC, Zhang J, Zhang XF, et al: Efficacy and safety of a recombinant hepatitis E vaccine in healthy adults; a large scale, randomised, double-blind placebo-controlled, phase 3 trial. Lancet 2010;376: 895-902.
- Mod.LL

